If you have music above all scenes and listen to them every day only briefly, for example in the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
Which almost every cell phone can do.
You don't have to check which music formats a mobile phone or player can process.
MP3 will create all, and most of the music you get will just be in this format.
The format is one of the most widely used, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better mobile phones also allow you to buy music online.
You only need to access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile internet, and you can already purchase a song or album.
This service can in itself be a striking argument for why you should buy a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is bad and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
Prices are not the lowest either.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of music sales (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry the phone with them.
If you feel like listening to something, grab the phone in the jacket pocket while the player is at home.
However, it depends whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can access the built-in speaker that almost every mobile phone has, but only the least MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage of the music phones will be the price for many.
The cheapest usually cost less than three thousand kroner.
For three and four thousand kroner, you'll get a decent walkman.
The biggest handicap for most will be that there are no normal headphones.
The best and most technically sophisticated phones with a 3.5 mm opening for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand kroner.
The advantage of the players lies in the easy operation.
The simplest - and not necessarily cheapest (see selection) - players can really be used by everyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the former normal cassette recorder or, for example, the record player is obvious.
There is no threat of a collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile Internet and a subsequent horrendous invoice for data transmissions.
Which device should you now reach for
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g.Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns are enough.
But respect.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are usually supported.
Only the most expensive can read 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, then grab Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to place more than 1100 crowns on the table.
Be among the more demanding listeners, prefer to take specialized mobile phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some of Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent control knobs for MP3, and the ease of use comes thus to that of a single MP3 player.
The furthest is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman mobile phones have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand kroner, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) provide you with MP3 players from the above mentioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, and the Czech providers offer virtually all the services offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't be long in coming.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the European Commission's final steps in regulating roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a battle announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that there is an extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who had often said in the past that there was no place for another provider in the Czech Republic, agrees with this.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has much chance (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is one more option - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought with it a significant price reduction, to which then also the classical mobile operators had to react.
Even before such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were similar voices to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, it doesn't take long to look for examples.
In February we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers, making it the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can concentrate on a much more specific target group.
In order to be able to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually stand out as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to focus on a non-clichetic target group.
This provider is specifically targeted at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and who they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also gain a foothold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone Miroslav Čepický's press spokesman also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of service provision."
In the Czech Republic, mobile operators believe that there is no chance
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region," says Jana Studničková, spokesman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything to ensure that there is no potential competitor.
Their interest in launching a virtual mobile provider has been demonstrated for some time by the group GTS Novera, which wants to take a further step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the area of corporate clients.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already achieved progress in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the press.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specificities over other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sršeň from the Telefónica O2 press office in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile press spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build on."
And she adds: "By the end of the year, hardly any virtual provider will appear on the T-Mobile network.
At this moment, we should already have a concrete offer in order to be able to think in such a short time."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický comments: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we see as the best from the customers' point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would be more competitive, which would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decline in profits.
So why should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ at the time, when U:fon came on the market, came from the company T-Mobile.
This is also demonstrated by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is the right argument for why you shouldn't allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
However, given this approach by mobile operators, the absolute lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not only the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately - unlike Great Britain and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
The latter holds the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, took its very typical attitude to this whole issue.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider through the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classical suppliers", said Kristián Chalupa from the External Relations Department of the ÚOHS in his reply to our request.
Such a formulation would not surprise suppliers’ representatives.
This is more than questionable by an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, ensures that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile telephone services."
However, pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not part of the ÚOHS’ interests.
What is really shocking in this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same petrol price at the petrol stations is surely only coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs of anti-competitive action in this matter, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The regulatory authority for telecommunications is also likely to lack the necessary tools to open up the mobile market to virtual providers," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile operator, logically, has a monopoly on its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if you do not follow this argument, it should at least be a warning to the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a quite common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act, it has not been possible to enforce the extension of ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay when nobody's looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
It is companies that spend their own price lists on mobile telecommunications services, but are only partially public.
Usually they are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Our own mobile telephone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar kind of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual terms that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end to the cooperation with the respective company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not talk around with those responsible for mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
In fact, from the activities of these companies, they receive not negligible profits, but at the same time - unlike the actual virtual providers - they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have it in full like the normal customers of mobile operators."
But the ČTÚ would at least have to seem strange.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an approach, why are they blocking a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of the providers that they know nothing about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers led to a significant drop in the price of the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have been created, the traditional providers have tried to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - a market which was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies intervened at this very moment, which did not seek to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and more followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing up the whole case like a hot potato.
On the basis of our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in competences is more than favourable in these cases.
But let's not throw the shotgun in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon start moving again.
If a provider permits the emergence of a virtual mobile provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other interested parties (to discriminate against them).
And the Czechs will finally not be more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Pick the Best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem "Where is my home country" at a ceremony on the occasion of the Czech State Day.
The hymn was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo vocals, in choir version and in an instrumental version.
The vocals were performed by Kateřina Kn’nková and Adam Plachetka.
The editors of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had already told the Czech Radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices for the solo versions, which are distinctive and popular.
"From the very beginning, I tried to keep a clear diction on both and then with the choir so that the text could be understood well, so that a harmony could come about," the conductor said.
The Czech national anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj first appeared on the stage of the State Theatre in 1834 in the originally Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music came from František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously accepted it.
The first verse of the song became an organic part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
