The Prague transport companies will also transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1st, 2008 will mark the beginning of the history of Prague's transport companies as a date when the first passengers who carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket will enter a subway, tram or bus.
About one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card can currently buy it.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and can play it on their chip card at the same time, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádra.. Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Since yesterday, the coupons are also available via the Internet on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use Internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
They buy the coupon on the Internet, which is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, travellers can also use a desk with trained staff to advise interested parties on internet purchases and to put the coupon on the map," said Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to the libraries, you can also play the electronic coupons on the opencard on self-service machines, which are installed in some underground vestibules.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, remind of ticket devaluers, the passengers have perhaps already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but it is supposed to be eighty by the end of the year," adds Opatrný.
The coupon is controlled by an automatic machine instead of the driver
The operation of the vending machines, which will work from tomorrow, is easy.
All you have to do is insert the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon plays itself.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which especially the inhabitants from municipalities of the region Central Bohemia reach the capital.
"On trains that are part of Prague's integrated traffic, the train attendants have readers that enable them to check the validity of the coupons according to time and zone," explains Filip Drápal from the Ropid organisation, explaining the ticket control. This organisation compiles the timetables for Prague's transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's ticket office.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the open card must be placed in a marked position at the side of the checkout.
Thus the driver controls the validity of the issued coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the issued coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information," says Drápal.
A passenger who does not drive suburban buses and no longer knows when the coupon expires can in turn go to the self-service machines where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information on the validity of its documents is displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the US
The Sudeten Germans had requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States in 1945.
This is evident from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian scientific library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would at least like to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the US President in 1945.
This can be seen, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian scientific library.
In the letter, the Germans of Krumau ask the American President not to allow the "Sudetengaus" - which was taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," says a letter signed with the words "people who care about the fate of the Sudeten".
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia makes the Sudeten Germans - in the knowledge of the Czech national character - suspect that they would expect brutality, recklessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the protection over the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that you, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this area, have acquitted a state that is foreign to us, which is trying to suppress and eliminate minorities and has done nothing whatsoever to contribute to the victory of the Allies," says the letter.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of revenge by the "Czech oppressors".
If the US President has doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it is sufficient that he initiate a referendum in the Böhmerwaldgau on whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the USA or live under the protective rule of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today's knowledge of post-war history, some contemporary witnesses believe that it paints a good picture of the Sudeten Germans' expectations at the time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans at least had to suspect that their deportation from the Republic would be negotiated, only a few of them admitted such a possibility at all.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Still others believed that they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
During the war he was employed as a German Budweiser in the Navy on the Baltic Sea.
When he was taken into British captivity at the end of the war and taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would fit them," said Chalupa.
In his opinion, none of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected that he would be expelled from the Republic on the basis of the Beneš decrees.
