Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cockroach flees in case of danger, does that mean that she also feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
Only how could they feel the same if they behave in a way similar to ours?
The Internet magazine " Edge" has been publishing contributions from famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far where we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and raise questions of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter rough terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it faces dead, flees, or attacks.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe in that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in the short-term memory and in the execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in man than in the rest of the primates and seems to be completely absent from other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic characteristic is likely to lie in the linguistic nature of man: since such a large part of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness does not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, however it may be, may differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then his research presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness, which should be more easily accessible scientifically.
One could examine the processes of consciousness of animals without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what happens in studies of the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one shifts rather to the neural correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: both may be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the emergence of visualization.
What is the result of the sensations?
I attribute it to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in one of its own activity conscious brain.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) proves memory.
In this way, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the Cortex, which distinguish primates and, in particular, humans.
Combined with linguistic nature, there are subtle gradations of feeling, because we can differentiate and categorize states with the help of words and grammar in order to attribute them to others as well as ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from more primitive activities in the body's sensory regions of the cortex and brain stem are similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, concentrates more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in cross-genre feelings.
In theory, I cannot disagree, but I think it is unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans probably also feels this way in both cases: How, however, can one check whether rats and humans feel the same if they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees at risk if she too feels fear?
