`Sangre de mayo': Book of Heroes by Garci
Inspired by `Episodios Nacionales' by Benito Pérez Galdós, José Luis Carci presents in `Sangre de mayo' the revised version of the famous Spanish uprising against the French. This is an admirable film in filmography, with about 15 million euros of investment for the shooting.
In this way, the Cineast has tried to 'present a lot of personalities and social analysis', which he has always admired in the works of the famous novelist, Carci explained today at the presentation of the film with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría at the beginning of a long list of actors.
`Sangre de mayo' with a film length of more than two and a half hours, will be presented this Friday in cinemas and later shown on Telemadrid as a four-hour miniseries.
José Luis Garci, a great fan of Galdós' literature, assures us that thanks to this shooting his 'childhood dream' came true. He owes this to Esperanza Aguirre, who commissioned him three years ago from the autonomous community of Madrid to make a commemorative film for the second century celebration on November 2nd in Madrid. Above all, because the story is based on 'Episodios Nacionales', he accepted the commission.
The total contribution of 15 million filmed by the autonomous community of Madrid offers Garci, as he added, the 'one-time possibility' with the help of decorations and corresponding clothing the image of 'confused Spain, who chose the false leader for the fight because the people had been put behind by the struggle for independence and under the rule of Ferdinand VII'.
However, the Cineast regrets that one could not count on the financing as with `Alatriste' or `Los fantasmas de Goya' (twice as high as with `Sangre de mayo'), so some scenes from the screenplay with Horacio Valcárcel, with whom Garci worked almost his entire career, could not be shot.
For this reason, Garci, who was also film director in 'Volver a empezar', has contributed through his usual way of working: he stood on stage with the actors with whom you have to rehearse first before you start shooting and for those who had not cast, he appeared 'humiliating' and creating respect, 'a part of the film director's profession consists of helping in theater and cinema to know what is happening in the cinema industry in which you work.'
Many actors he encounters in 'Sangre de mayo' must repeat in front of his camera, as in the case of Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
Garci, Oscar candidate in four nominations (of which he has won one), is of the opinion and assured that none of the three candidates representing Spain before the Academy of Hollywood this year represents a young generation of Spanish filmography. Neither 'Sangre de mayo', nor 'Siete mesas de billar francés' nor, finally, the selected film 'Los girasoles ciegos'.
Garci does not expect any awards for this film.
'In the beginning you think you work for the offspring, later you realize that it's only for flourishing, and now you're happy when you've produced a movie,' says Garci after more than 30 years of working.
Isabel Bayón recalls the memory of the dancer from Seville Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville adores a dancer who is also from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalane (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and her mother Andalucian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the Triana district and when she was three years old her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and expert in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first fighters for the emancipation of the woman, such as Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, vegetarian, and advocated the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
Isabel Bayón was fascinated by the life of this woman, who left her mark on the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe between the wars.
'I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this role to me, which seemed impossible to me.'
'We're not trying to tell about her life, but to preserve her esprit,' said the flamenco dancer.
Your dance bases have helped me a lot in Flamenco.
'The Dance of the Butterfly' seemed to me like Guajira, for example, or 'the Dance of the Snake' like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I was told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area,' she claims.
The production looks forward to two extraordinary collaborations: Miguel Poveda, who will sing again for Isabel at one of her performances, as he did in `La puerta abitera'; and with flamenco master Matilde Coral, who, for once, wanted to work together with one of her former students.
`Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I am very honored.'
The production also anticipates musical composition and the guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the singing of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Júarez, he 'takes over the role of the companion of the artists who were divas, to whom he falls in love again and again.'
This work also tells in a certain way about the life of this woman, who became known in places as far away as India, the United States or Russia and also throughout Europe, although she normally lived in London.
'I wanted to call her back to memory, because I think she is one of the women who have an enormous influence on a certain epoch and whose works no one knows any more today and therefore appreciates her even less,' Bayón claims.
The performance takes place today at 20:30 at the Theatre Lope de Vega.
