Sarkozy meets angry fishermen
Before flying to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make another detour to Brittany.
In view of the determined attitude of the fishermen who blocked access to several Breton and Norman ports on Monday, the French President decided to arrive Tuesday morning at the port of Guilvinec in the Finistère to meet their representatives.
The latter promised to receive him 'with a constructive spirit' and hope that he will come with 'concrete proposals'.
The President's visit takes place at the same time as a General Assembly of the Crisis Committee, established by the Breton fishermen to enforce measures in the face of the extreme rise in the price of diesel, which has reached a record average of more than EUR 1.14 per litre.
According to David Martinon, spokesman of the Elysée Palace, 'the President will discuss with them possible solutions to help their companies become competitive again, and to secure the conditions of employment and the payment of seafarers'.
Sarkozy is expected with determination by the fishermen.
Tuesday morning they led protest marches in Morbihan and Calvado, which caused traffic jams of almost ten kilometres.
The port of Quiberon was also blocked, but the connections to Belle-île did not break down.
The Quiberon Peninsula was closed with a barrier.
Already on Monday the sailors expressed their determination by burning tires and pallets in front of the fuel depots of the ports of Brest and Lorient from the early morning, while demonstrations were held in Concarneau or Saint-Brieuc.
The movement expanded to other ports on the Atlantic coast and the English Channel, such as Sables d'Olonnes, in Vendée, where the fishing boats did not go out, or Le Havre, where about twenty boats blocked the maneuvers of the merchant ships.
The fishermen of Turballe and Croisic in Loire-Atlantique dissolved the blockade of the important total refinery in Donges in the evening.
The Boulogne-sur-Mer decided to wait for the meeting to take place on Wednesday at the Ministry before deciding on possible measures.
In fact, the Crisis Committee in Guilvinec must decide on the reactions to the movement and its participation in the discussion planned at the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by the leaders of the National Fisheries Committee who did not support their movement.
'The strike will continue', because 'the fishermen will not give in at any point' and 'do not want to go to Paris', announced Liliane Cariou, President of the Lorient Fisheries Committee, for example.
The professional fishermen who do not pay taxes on diesel currently cost the litre about 50 cents, but they think that the profitability limit of a boat can only be reached with diesel for less than 30 cents per litre.
