Charest bets on the north
The Prime Minister does not rule out the opening of elections before the end of the year.
As soon as the General Assembly of the Liberal Party was over, Jean Charest went yesterday to Jean-Talon in Quebec, where the new Health Minister Yves Bolduc (leftist) tried to be elected in today's partial election.
'Moving the course of our last big border in the north': This is the long-term goal that Jean Charest presented yesterday with visual means at the General Assembly of the Quebec Liberal Party in Levis, following entirely the guidelines.
During his lecture, a kind of picture mill was projected behind him.
On three huge screens, spectacular images of hydroelectric power plants, mines, viewed from Quebec in Google Maps, maps, etc.
Large funds as during the parliamentary term.
By the way, the Prime Minister refused to rule out the possibility of holding the elections this autumn, even if he said that his schedule was very full.
The 'Plan Nord' is the fourth element of a 'vision' that the Prime Minister claims to have for Quebec, namely that of a 'new economic area' which provides for an agreement with France on labour, an agreement between Canada and Europe and agreements with Ontario.
Although it has been frequently mentioned in the Prime Minister's speeches in recent times, the opening of the North - the northern area at 49th latitude - has never been the subject of a presentation.
The Prime Minister, however, confined himself to explaining why the North was 'a jewel with enormous potential', but did not mention a date, investment sums or precise priorities for the upcoming projects.
At the most, a few perspectives on what could be done more: water, forest, but especially mining, benefiting from the growth of emerging economies and the renewal of public infrastructure.
According to Mr. Charests, the north possesses 'nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium and even diamonds'.
This 'territory twice as large as France' 'is near us, is in Quebec.
It is not only in our vicinity, it is in us', he stressed, as to show clearly that he is trying to realize a national founding dream.
Quebec has grown greatly by its connection with the north, he emphasized: the road to gold in Abitibi, the technique of Quebec, the James Bay.
'It's ours, it's our future,' he added, after having taken a theatrical break to look at the huge map behind him.
The North, 70% of Quebec's territory, includes a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always demanded, the Prime Minister told the press.
'This is a traditional attitude that all governments have pursued.
There is a border line on which there has been no agreement for a very long time, when the opportunity arises, I will take this position again on behalf of the government,' he said.
Moreover, 'with climate change, we need to rethink our vision of the North', he explained, and talked about the Northwest Passage, which will be passable all year round due to the ice melt.
Against this new geopolitical background, the Prime Minister believes that it is almost a duty to occupy this area.
And the inhabitants of the area, the natives and the Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec government would deal very carefully with them and that they would benefit from this project, especially the young.
Two former ministers of various parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former Pekist representative of Ungava), have already begun discussions in some thirty communities.
A committee of ministers led by Benoît Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (transport and mineral resources) occupies an important place, has begun work.
The Prime Minister does not exclude a large assembly, 'not necessarily a summit', but an opportunity at which 'one will create a common vision'.
The development of the North will also be in line with the principles of sustainable development.
Plan North will be 'spoken, regulated and environmentally friendly', he promised.
Jean Charest described this 'vision' as being a continuation of those liberal prime ministers who were in office before him.
Like the liberals who were in office before us, we have rethought to transform the challenges into new growth and development opportunities.
By the way, this was one of the repeatedly raised themes of the weekend, which was opened on Friday with a large cocktail party to celebrate the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage's takeover of the party leadership.
One of the adopted decisions provides for the renaming of the Beauharnois power station to Adélard-Godbout dam.
'From Godbout, who created Hydro-Quebec, through Lesage, who achieved the silent revolution and the nationalization of water electricity, to Bourassa, who made the James Bay, our party always knew how to determine the future,' explained Jean Charest.
To the press, he referred to another conservative project, namely the 'Roads to the North' programme by John Diefenbaker, Prime Minister from 1957 to 1963.
With regard to the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam project, Mr Charest stressed that it was scheduled to be put into operation in 2012.
'This remains between us, but I intend to be there,' he confided to his party members, which caused those storms.
The Prime Minister, who said in April that there would be no elections in 2008, and certainly also in 2009, has indeed not yet ruled out the possibility of holding an election this autumn, which is possible for him under the law.
However, he stressed that his agenda was full, especially because of a Community Council mission in China and a summit between Quebec and New York.
The weekend General Assembly provided the Liberal Party leader with a platform of nationalist plans, especially 'constitutional objectives', which were readily adopted: the PLQ calls in particular for recognition of the 'specificity of Quebec' in the Constitution.
It also wants Quebec to appoint members of the Canadian Broadcasting and Telecommunications Council and to have a veto over decisions taken in Quebec.
On the opposition side, the guidelines of the Plan North were taken up with scepticism.
The leader of the Parti Québécois, Pauline Marois, has brought about the development of the Nord-du-Quebec, which was introduced by the Landry government in 2001.
According to her, when she came to power in 2003, the liberal government refused to apply it.
If she had done so, 'we would have gone much further today', Mrs Marois judged at the side of her candidate in Jean-Talon (where the election is taking place today) Françoise Mercure.
