So the time has come when there is no morale left: one can arbitrarily abuse, torture and lock up a Canadian citizen, according to the wishes of a head of government who is still supported only by the minority (may he belong entirely to the minority after 14 October...).
Many voters believe that they can find their salvation in a party that preaches virtue, law and order, but they do not see that this government has renounced what constituted the reputation and dignity of our country.
The shame, Mr. Toews, lies in this release, and nowhere else.
Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice-Director General of the Barrick Gold Mine in Canada.
This confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world's largest gold mining company sought a slander lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small penniless publishing house, with the aim of opening a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of libel lawsuits, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactics of these unequal struggles are, moreover, often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual settlement that silences the other side and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the question again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things to public opinion.
In contrast to what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates usually take place in Canada through the exchange of ideas, and not through stick hits.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened up a real debate through which newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent inspection teams could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes the petitions and letters to support the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement aside.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can at the same time ask for a 'public' debate and yet disregard the opinions of this very public?
Apparently, in the vice-president's world, this word only includes the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a very narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public who supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada does so mainly because it rejects the brutal attitude of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not within a framework that many perceive as a gag suit (in the course of the 'public debate' Barrick Gold has just addressed a demand to the authors of Noir Canada in which they ask them not to use this term anymore...).
Apart from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's lawsuit is a direct attack on freedom for academic research and truth-finding that is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss topics that the rich companies of this world do not like, then who else can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to deal with debates and disagreements and how to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she does not want to have a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit this kind of unjustified lawsuit.
Wall Street Rescue - Democrats and Republicans Understand
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most comprehensive economic recovery plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the plan of $700 billion, which is to stop the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months, still needs to be adopted by the two congress chambers.
The main features are: better control of MEPs' practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to secure repayment of public funds, new injunctions to limit the number of houses pledged due to arrears, and the right to monitor salaries paid to the executives of the supported companies.
The American financial secretary Henry Paulson, the president of the Chamber of Deputies Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, the good news, after a two-day negotiation marathon.
'We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective on the market,' said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
'Everything was done to protect the real economy and the American people from the price crisis on Wall Street,' explained the Democrat.
'This is the basic point: if we do not, the trauma, chaos and unrest in the daily life of the Americans will be enormous,' explained Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, for fear of the effect that a renewed failure would have had on the mood of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two US presidential candidates who took part in the negotiations only late showed themselves to be more in favour of the agreement, but without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on adding certain resolutions to the agreement, especially those that would allow owners to keep their homes, and those that would affect the salaries of the executives of the state-saved companies.
"When you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain people, that is nothing to be congratulated for.
But these measures are necessary,' he said on American television stations.
When asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied: 'I would like to know the details first, but I hope so.
"The guiding principles I have read [show] that this is one thing that we all will have to digest, and with which we will be able to progress.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,' he said.
The 700 billion dollar plan is aimed at using taxpayers' money
It comes 14 months after a crisis, triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble, which initially led to the collapse of high-risk mortgage loans (subprime) before it expanded to other forms of more widespread bonds (PCAA), and eventually led to a freeze of financial strength and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who failed the first attempt to reach agreement last week.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain 'poisonous' assets of societies in distress should only be secured by the government and not be bought, it is believed to escape the impasse.
To round off the perspective for all in Congress, an injunction has also been added, stating that if the government were to make losses with this program within five years, it could then levy new taxes in order to get back its invested capital.
The new plan provides for the payment of an initial sum of 250 billion, to which a further 100 billion can be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion must be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In return for his help, Washington receives shares in the supported companies that pay him dividends in the event of profits and that can sell it again when the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will have the possibility to stop the attachment proceedings concerning the housing linked to the real estate loans covered by this plan, and also to set deadlines for repayment and severance payments to the executives of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on him already today, and the Senate then on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
In fact, there were further votes against this plan yesterday, both from the Republicans and the Democrats.
'Of course Washington does not understand us,' declared Republican Scott Garett, member of the Chamber's Financial Commission, to his voters.
'Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of asking taxpayers to pay.'
Democratic MP Brad Sherman, head of a group in Congress called 'the caucus of skeptics', presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
`Four hundred excellent economic professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to tell us: we ask Congress not to be pressured, and to consider carefully what course to take,' he said yesterday.
At the same time, we in Europe were once again shown that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying up its competitor, which is in great difficulty since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US dollars) in the crisis due to the risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
'This is not lost money, said the Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
To compensate, we are given the right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what savers and households appreciate now that uncertain times are announcing themselves.'
During this time, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government was in the process of nationalizing another bank in distress by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all current loans from Bank Bradford and Bringley, of which over 41 billion (75.5 billion US dollars) were from real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the UK bank.
After Northern Rock, Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank the British government has had to nationalise since the beginning of this financial crisis.
