What was produced in the invoice factory of Hammerg &amp; Co.?
On 8 October, the trial of Jáno's contract and his accomplices will begin.
In particular, the accused are accused of participating in organised crime, as well as grossly negligent damage and business fraud, and other criminal acts, including forgery of documents.
According to the Public Prosecutor’s Office, the funds generated by the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often covered by counterfeit invoices.
State funds and subsidies from the self-government - a total of HUF 65 million - are said to have partly been paid into the funds of the organisation Fiatal Baloldal, partly into the private funds of individual funds.
According to the investigation authorities, fictitious invoices were submitted when the tender funds were collected and the clubs were not supposed to have fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the bills have been forged.
The invoice blocks were bought at the market of Józsefváros, the round seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies to issue the invoices was taken on the tour north of Lake Balaton, to which István Lados was awarded by János.
In the course of this "exploratory tour" Lados was to find pensions and restaurants.
He demanded bills for the consumptions so that he could later issue bills based on these templates for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, and the self-government of Budapest.
The majority of these invoices are said to have been manipulated by István Lados and his accomplice, András Ri, who, according to our information, was responsible for the constitution of the relevant reports.
One of the destinations of Lados' "exploratory tour" was a beer restaurant.
According to two invoices issued by Hammer and Co in 2003, the catering company is said to have hosted the ninety-strong group of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
But now the head of the company states that such a large group would not have fit into the restaurant at once.
Another invoice issued in the summer of 2002 by the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also showed serious form and content errors.
In a guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj, which has only three rooms and can accommodate no more than ten people at the same time, 130 guests are said to have stayed according to the bill.
