"The vast majority of Roma youths do not have middle school education, and due to poor primary education only a small part of them can obtain a university degree".
Furthermore, Járóka stressed that education was a fundamental human right, which had a key role to play in asserting other human rights.
Investing in early education for Roma children could strengthen the economy of EU member states.
