"We have taken two steps forward and one backwards, but the most important thing is that the dialogue between Belarus and the EU has begun," said Alexander Milinkevich to our paper.
According to the opposition candidate of the 2006 presidential election, it is desirable to continue, although "the powerful have been afraid to let even one opposition candidate into parliament".
The opposition is not planning any protest measures in the light of the results, but rather is trying to make clear to the voters the need for economic reform.
"We have many problems here - the opposition newspapers have to be printed in Russia, the local authorities are putting stones in our way when it comes to distribution, but yet I see that more and more people are supporting change, even the older ones," Milinkevich said, alluding to the fact that not even the most supported pensioners agree with the Lukashenko regime, whose only merit is the production of social security.
"Thanks to the country's indebtedness and the increase in the trade deficit, it is only a matter of time before the "social security" that calls for the silence of a cemetery begins to crumble," Milinkevich says.
Unlike opposition politicians, Russian observers have called the elections democratic.
Sergei Lebedev, Head of the Mission of the Commonwealth of Independent States, told Ria Novosti, the news agency, "People believe the deeds, not the words." The absence of the opposition is therefore proof of the maturity of the Belarusian voters.
Brunetta: "From now on, breakfast will be served before work"
