Napolitano: "Prevention of accidents at work is crucial"
Every day, 2500 accidents at work occur in Italy, three people die and 27 remain incapacitated for life.
For 2007, data from the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul Lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were about 1200.
These figures demonstrate the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) in all provinces of Italy will celebrate the 58th National Day for the Victims of Accidents at Work in order to draw the attention of social institutions and media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention in the workplace is," confirms the President of the Republic Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention in the workplace, to the protection of injured workers, to aid the families of the victims and to the awareness of public opinion".
"An outraged "basta" has risen to this; understandable in tragedies, which, measured by their magnitude, cause some vortex in the media and public sympathy. However, everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events, which can even be repeated in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide that "there is definitely also a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness of the school environment by young people who are nourishing the world of work are of particular importance.
It is our duty to pay attention to this phenomenon and not to divert attention from its social seriousness. It is necessary to put into effect and improve a legislative standard.
For his part, the President of the Chamber, Gianfranco Fini, stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency, which insults the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards firm rules aimed at putting an end to the problem".
"Data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not exclude the fact that the number of work-related deaths is far too high," stresses Anmil President Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this "positive tendency" to mean less attention. That's exactly what causes the tragedy in the end."
"How do you think that you are doing too little to counter the phenomenon of accidents? You can fight against it through various actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary – Mercandelli said; but also stronger measures to educate the workers who are already starting at school."
"Another effort is needed - he adds - in terms of communication and awareness of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that represents a social emergency is in demand."
Mercandelli also referred to "the progressive deterioration of protection for the victims of accidents at work" and denounced the "abolition of the social system against which we are fighting in recent years".
"The aim is therefore to give the worker a guarantee on insurance, so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not depend on voluntary or accidental donations, which are decided from time to time by a legislator."
Mp3 player under charge: danger of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as Mp3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which cites the opinion of the Csrseri (scientific committee on current and recently identified health risks) of the EU in a report published today in Brussels.
"The report – as one notes – shows that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music with portable music equipment for at least five years a week for more than one hour a day risk permanent loss of hearing."
"I am worried that such a large number of young people, who usually put portable music devices and mobile phones at a high volume, will irretrievably damage their hearing without knowing it," says Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific findings – according to the EU – show a clear risk that pushes too fast action.
What really matters is to raise consumer awareness and make this information a common good.
In the light of these scientific findings, we must re-examine existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology".
Brussels had appointed the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music equipment among young people.
"Scientists - as the EU Communication concludes - confirm that there is a legitimate concern and that the European Commission, together with the other EU members and stakeholders, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise from portable music equipment and similar equipment".
There is already a European standard which limits the level of noise from portable music equipment to 100 dB, and concerns about the damage that could result from too much noise pollution.
This damage can be very limited by resorting to solutions such as reducing the volume and length of the noise exposure.
In its report, the Scientific Committee of the European Union points out that when users of portable music devices hear loud music only five hours a week (more than 89 decibels) so that the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who exceed this limit risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This would therefore represent 5-10% of users of such equipment, the number of which can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the European Union.
Roma, Alemanno kicks off the "Commission for the Future of the Capital"
We're starting today, it's supposed to be over in March, we're taking stock in June.
This is the procedure laid down by the Capitol for the work of the "Commission for the Future of the Capital of Rome". The Commission met this morning in the new headquarters behind the Caracalla thermal baths.
In six months' time, President Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will work out the lines of leadership for Rome.
Once the project is completed, the City Council and the Municipal Council will evaluate the analyses and projects in order to be able to present in June the strategic plan for Rome with the "official stamp" of the Capitol and the Lord Mayor Gianni Alemanno.
"The Commission is absolutely independent and all political, social and cultural opinions are represented in it", - stresses Alemanno. "It will make proposals for a development plan for Rome, whose political leaders remain the city council and the municipal council.
There is no redistribution of responsibilities, only the will to have a place where one can develop a great project for Rome.
Their task will be completed in March and the Commission will be dissolved, as such a project must have a timed end point.
In June - as the Lord Mayor announces - we will present the strategic plan in which we will use the work done by the Commission".
Anyone who questions the competence of the Commission, since their opinion is lacking in commitment, responds to Alemanno: "Everything depends on the work that the Commission will do and on the quality of its proposals.
If, as in France, the Attali Commission delivers high-quality results – and this will certainly be the case in Rome – then its contribution will be fundamental.
Too often politics deals with the everyday problems and emergencies that occur from time to time.
We, on the other hand, want to have a longer period of time in mind, so that in a deeper perspective we can work seriously on the development of Rome and the future of the city".
The Lord Mayor of Rome attaches great importance to clarifying the following: "This Commission is neither a useless institution nor a wreck: it is absolutely free, it will not cost the Roman citizens a cent and it will make us think. It will occupy the best heads of the capital".
According to Alemanno, "it is necessary to have a strategic plan that is neither hermetic nor static in order to enable our city to make a qualitative leap - which it really needs - and thus to take a joint step into the future".
A future, according to the Mayor of Rome, which "will not only be limited to the current local borders, but will look much further", not only in terms of the role of Rome as a metropolis and political capital of Italy, but also as the future capital of Europe and the Mediterranean."
