The elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the White House's $700 billion savings package: a large part of the Americans were and is more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's issue of the New York Times, which reports how the crisis in progress divides the Republican party, which is increasingly splitting into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and business community, and those neoconservatives that are hostile to "them in Washington" and the financial world and, above all, win voters in the south and the center of states.
This part of the party owes its rise above all to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
However, this example, which has just been mentioned, is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake heralds or even already represents: not only in the United States, but also throughout the West and perhaps beyond it, will be affected by it.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the long-awaited events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis is a decline in banking and financial institutions which have close links with foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the assets of private households living in a single state.
This is an immediate political problem for governments: how to behave towards the families concerned, which are also an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis thus appears economically global, whereas politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have been sidelined and lost its right to speak: the clear proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into different national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and above all distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became ever more serious, only the US is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign help.
In addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two conditions that cannot be overvalued – under certain circumstances – which no international organisation or market will otherwise be able to rely on in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance which has recently been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely now that we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked empire, a realm of increasingly differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we suddenly have to find out how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
While all of these can be transported from one place to the other in the world, they are connected to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory is in advantage over another who lives in an area without harvest, without water or without oil.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a brief insertion.
Who territory, who government, who says politics, thus also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to generate two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leaderships, that is, the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy that have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a sense, still disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerance, an image of inefficiency, a sense of distance, all of which is directed at a whole class of Western managers.
It seems to be the conviction among large sections of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is presented to the majority as becoming more and more foreign and traditional.
The demand for leadership is thus fueling a branched but powerful movement of the disempowerment of the leading class and the traditional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of the voters and in the sudden reversal of the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, about the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, towards the rebellion of the American deputies against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value regarding what is going on today in the lower social strata of the West and is being intensified and driven even further by the financial crisis and to over-dimensionality.
In view of all this, it would be simply exaggerated to speak of a "rebel of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The super glue that lets go up on walls
Defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and climb up walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which seems to have almost reached its goal.
With an adhesive applied on an area of only 2.5 qcm, the researchers succeeded in fixing a body weighing 100 kg on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American journal has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the adhesives already used, which use a special carbon structure called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged into a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang from the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
The tests carried out with various materials such as glass Teflon and sandpaper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the ability to hold the feet of reptiles and at the same time "to remove them from the wall without problems", says Liming Dai, researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
"This material could be used as a transitory adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe so, but the researchers think of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other areas of application could fall within the space sector.
So for the moment, the superheroes have to wait.
THE OTHER TYPE OF RESEARCH – the University of Berkeley, California, is also dedicated to a new type of glue.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the Californian scientists present an adhesive made of microfibers that, like hair, clean themselves from the dust by moving on a surface and thus always maintain perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Be careful of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed mainly in summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, can cause serious health damage if they are taken with certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points to the risk of both packaged and fresh fruit juices associated with medication intake. During the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again sounded the alarm: a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is sufficient to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital medicines to the extent that they are virtually eliminated and thus endanger the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs, such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
MEDICATIONS IN DRIVER – In a report two years ago, the same agency had warned doctors and patients of the dangers of this mixture, and stressed the need to take care of what is being drunk in connection with drugs such as diazepane or metadon.
IT IS NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually forwarded immediately to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change consumer information.
It is therefore advisable to read the package leaflet at all times and, if there is still some uncertainty, to ask a pharmacist or doctor," the Ansa Agency expert stresses.
