Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package appears
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the Open Source software, as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office, is gaining an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in the public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now presenting itself with some new features to the public: in addition to a revised and now spartan designed initial menu, a completely guaranteed compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x has finally been achieved, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest standard ISO version.
In addition, the compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice, has been improved.
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes sending via email easier. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics editing modules and at the same time preserve the original appearance of the page.
So you can now also generate "hybride" PDF files, which extend the typical graphic of Adobe format by the elements of a table and a word processing system.
The collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited by several hands by different users, thus avoiding conflicts in the event of changes; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a question in order to guarantee a better correction procedure.
Some companies are about to publish different OpenOffice functions on the Internet (on the cloud), while the final result will be made public in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download on the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. Thus it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Except for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request you can have the installation CD sent to your home or office.
However, if cost-free can be an incentive for the dissemination of the programme in private households, it is also particularly in the area of business, where OpenOffice could succeed the big throw: after all, various institutions of public administration and schools have already moved to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of training, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word corresponding text creation program; Calc, the table program, which aims at a displacement of Excel; Impress, for creating presentations like with PowerPoint; Dbase to operate databases instead of the more known access; and most recently Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a goal that can be easily exceeded with already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
