Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema – the cities close their historical cinemas
The historical cinemas close due to the favored multiplexkinos.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the major urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of the exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means in the long run death for the one-room cinema in the centre. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the characteristics of a cultural crime.
It is mostly historical places full of memories that are affected, "to lose it is like losing a friend with whom one has travelled a piece of street full of emotions", says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", which 20 years ago brought him the Oscar and the great prize of Cannes. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
The figures supplied by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas has had to close; most of these mines paid for the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The regions most affected include Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany with 44 cinemas and Lombardy with 41 cinemas.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplexkinos, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years Lombardy leads the lists, 81 it is in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "although it is useful that new structures emerge, the first priority is the preservation of the already existing one, because if a hall closes in the city, not all its regular customers are ready to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here remains the missing budget for the fund of the trade association external eight: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to approximately 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be needed".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city which, due to the fears surrounding the old cinemas, has decided to protect it by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first such agreement in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting the traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the planned measures are also tax advantages for cinema operators as well as advantages for the public with regard to local transport: it will be allowed to travel to the traffic-limited areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It is a welcome initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also develop new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex halls, because after all, the audience of today is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
For 25 years I have lived in Rome; when I pass by the Rialto or Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to avoid seeing the dusty posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adapt the community's decisions to the interests of the Piromalli mafia group.
The accusations by the Anti-Mafia Office of Calabria against Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the Municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia business, are serious.
In handcuffs were also taken Gioacchino Piromalli, the older mediator between the clan and the public administration, as well as his nephew: the lawyer, who bears the same name as the clan's boss, had already been sentenced for involvement in criminal mafia associations, at that time to a compensation amount of 10 million euros.
"Regarding any moral and legal norm," the lawyers wrote, "the two local administrations decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli money for consulting activities."
"Thus the mafia group was made possible – according to the judges – to enter the town halls on an official way and to co-determine the politics of the public administration."
The President of the Regional Committee of Calabria, Agazio Loiero, does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to encounter links between local administrations and organised crime." "There are places where the Mafia's concentration is greater than in others where such links are practically inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who maintain a white vest."
The arrests of this morning follow those of last July, with which, according to the police, the clan Piromalli was beheaded.
Since the end of last April, Gioia Tauro’s municipal council had been dissolved, but as early as 1991 – and even then due to alleged links between organised crime and the local administration – local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the centre-right coalition after the May 2006 election.
He screamed scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He was accused of inventing everything for political and strategic reasons in the Vice-Minister of the Interior, Marco Minniti, but the judges explain in connection with this morning's arrest warrant that the Piromalli clan had even dared to apply for a change to the A3 project.
A wiretapping operation in connection with the Dal Torrione case investigation has shown a willingness to meet the wishes of an entrepreneur, who is known to be a representative of the large Piromalli group – making public administration measures identical to the interests of this clan."
When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly come up
It is a non-drinking source of money that covers over 70% of the planet's surface and only now do the world's major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking at, and are also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been under consideration and studied for 70 years; it is not by chance that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980 the idea of marine energy was gassed, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy needs could be met by the energies generated by ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides are added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are relying on marine energy production.
"Chevron investigates these technologies," says the spokesman of a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, and considers the possibility of working with us."
This is about obtaining a permit from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that oil is still being mined by the United States in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; even if the details are not known, observers speak of an increasing interest.
Technologies that need to be improved.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still on the rise, not least because the last doubts from environmentalists have not yet been resolved.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small scale and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are various possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned plants of this type, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy gained could also be used for military installations.
However, Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a park latz using submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotation.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Production Research, a particular interest now deserves the potential that lies in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of electricity.
It is tidal energy that led states like New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
